the different departments,

23:32.500 --> 23:33.956
see how you're
doing things these days.

23:33.960 --> 23:35.496
That sounds good.

23:35.500 --> 23:37.411
-[phone beeps]
-Schoenville Markets.

23:37.420 --> 23:39.661
I got a big lunch meeting
with these guys today.

23:39.670 --> 23:41.410
All right, do your thing.

23:41.420 --> 23:42.705
Okay.
We'll see you later.

23:42.710 --> 23:44.246
Yeah.

23:57.500 --> 23:59.707
You tryin' to sneak
Cap'n Crunch
into my galley?

23:59.710 --> 24:01.701
What are you,
like, six?

24:01.710 --> 24:04.668
It's not mine, bitch.

24:04.670 --> 24:06.661
Hey, it's got ten essential
vitamins and minerals in it.

24:06.670 --> 24:08.706
[Chris]
It's my Cap'n Crunch.

24:08.710 --> 24:11.110
You mean you slobs haven't
cleaned out the pantry

24:11.120 --> 24:12.747
since I've been gone?

24:12.750 --> 24:14.206
-Chris!
-Hey, man.

24:14.210 --> 24:15.916
-Dude!
-You good?

24:15.920 --> 24:17.205
[laughing] Oh, man!

24:17.210 --> 24:19.075
Hey, buddy.
You good?

24:19.080 --> 24:20.911
What the hell are you
doing here, man?

24:20.920 --> 24:22.660
Well, you know,

24:22.670 --> 24:24.911
I missed the stink of chopped
squid and cod's blood.

24:24.920 --> 24:27.536
Um, I don't know
about this, man.

24:27.540 --> 24:28.700
They're gonna find
you here, dude.

24:28.710 --> 24:30.371
They already have.

24:30.380 --> 24:33.417
This guy from the facility
tracked me down.

24:33.420 --> 24:34.705
Wait, all the way
to Alaska?

24:34.710 --> 24:36.496
Yeah, I know. Crazy.

24:36.500 --> 24:38.570
But, apparently,
all he wanted to know about

24:38.580 --> 24:41.788
was the nurse that I drove
to Libbey Beach with.

24:41.790 --> 24:45.169
So 3,000 miles to find out
about a nurse?

24:45.170 --> 24:47.786
Uh, yeah,
she's wanted, dude,

24:47.790 --> 24:49.781
for, like,
multiple homicides.

24:49.790 --> 24:52.372
I was ridin' with
a legit psycho killer.

24:52.380 --> 24:54.496
I'm luclq to be alive.

24:54.500 --> 24:56.661
That and because
that mermaid almost
killed you before that.

24:56.670 --> 24:59.571
Uh, dude says
it wasn't a mermaid.

24:59.580 --> 25:01.536
What exactly did they
take from us?

25:01.540 --> 25:02.529
He tell you that?

25:02.540 --> 25:04.610
Said it was a rare fish.

25:04.620 --> 25:05.609
[laughs]

25:05.620 --> 25:06.951
Okay, yeah, whatever.

25:06.960 --> 25:08.370
Look, man, yeah, maybe...

25:08.380 --> 25:09.870
maybe it is some big cover-up.

25:09.880 --> 25:11.780
Who knows?

25:11.790 --> 25:13.371
But I'm done runnin'.

25:13.380 --> 25:15.200
Look, if they found me
up there,

25:15.210 --> 25:16.700
they're gonna find me
anywhere.

25:16.710 --> 25:18.746
I'd rather be in danger
here with you guys

25:18.750 --> 25:20.911
than all alone

25:20.920 --> 25:22.785
up in Butthole, Alaska.

25:22.790 --> 25:26.669
So this here is
top shelf, my friend.

25:26.670 --> 25:31.698
We can crack it open
if you give me my job back.

25:31.710 --> 25:33.746
-All right.
-Yeah?

25:33.750 --> 25:36.241
[Xander] Yeah. All right.
I mean, I'd rather
have that mermaid,

25:36.250 --> 25:38.070
but I guess we'll have to
settle for your sorry ass.

25:38.080 --> 25:39.616
-It's not a mermaid.
-Yeah, whatever.

25:39.620 --> 25:41.702
-Just shut up and pour.
-All right.

25:43.830 --> 25:45.661
Petty Officer Montero?

25:45.670 --> 25:47.661
Yes, sir?

25:47.670 --> 25:49.160
Just picked up
a report from the local
sheriff's office

25:49.170 --> 25:50.990
at Bristol Cove,
Washington.

25:51.000 --> 25:54.572
Seems a young woman
assaulted a 250-pound
dock worker.

25:54.580 --> 25:56.992
Sir, what would you
like me to do about it, sir?

25:57.000 --> 26:00.379
I need you to get me
a detailed description
of the suspect.

26:09.540 --> 26:11.826
Are you gonna
be okay by yourself?

26:11.830 --> 26:13.491
Okay.

26:13.500 --> 26:14.660
Yes.

26:24.710 --> 26:26.325
Pretty.

26:26.330 --> 26:27.661
This?

26:27.670 --> 26:29.206
I bought it for a wedding.

26:29.210 --> 26:30.666
It's not my thing really.

26:30.670 --> 26:32.706
I'm having lunch
with Ben's mother.

26:32.710 --> 26:34.666
Mother.

26:34.670 --> 26:36.991
What is mother?

26:37.000 --> 26:38.740
Uh... mother.

26:40.460 --> 26:41.529
Well...

26:46.250 --> 26:47.911
Family.

26:47.920 --> 26:49.239
Mother.

26:51.960 --> 26:53.916
You have mother?

26:53.920 --> 26:57.913
Uh, yes, but she's gone.

26:57.920 --> 26:59.035
Dead?

26:59.040 --> 27:00.246
No, I--

27:02.000 --> 27:03.820
I don't know.

27:03.830 --> 27:06.572
Just gone.

27:09.920 --> 27:13.959
Family important.

27:13.960 --> 27:16.747
Yes, family is, uh...

27:16.750 --> 27:18.536
love.

27:19.880 --> 27:22.610
You are love.

27:22.620 --> 27:23.780
Oh.

27:25.750 --> 27:26.876
Thank you.

27:32.330 --> 27:34.571
To stay safe
if you need it.

27:40.080 --> 27:42.162
I miss you.

27:43.620 --> 27:44.780
I missed you, too.

28:03.750 --> 28:04.956
Bye-bye.

28:06.540 --> 28:09.168
Uh, yeah, okay.

28:09.170 --> 28:10.706
Bye.

28:14.040 --> 28:15.450
[door opens]

28:17.000 --> 28:18.376
[door closes]

28:23.960 --> 28:26.167
Let me show you
the line here.

28:26.170 --> 28:28.661
This is from a load
of sockeye we got
this morning.

28:30.500 --> 28:33.037
It seems like a lot
a bycatch mixed up
in the haul.

28:33.040 --> 28:35.076
Yep.
It's a new client.

28:35.080 --> 28:37.958
Coastal Mills
has been buying,
like, anything we got.

28:37.960 --> 28:39.416
Coastal Mills?

28:39.420 --> 28:41.035
I've never hard of 'em.

28:41.040 --> 28:43.747
Nobody has
until about a month ago.

28:43.750 --> 28:45.957
Trucks just started
showing up.

28:45.960 --> 28:47.245
They've been buying
the stuff up

28:47.250 --> 28:50.162
faster than we can
load it in the bins.

28:50.170 --> 28:51.990
[Xander] Yo, Ben!

28:52.000 --> 28:54.070
Got a second?

28:54.080 --> 28:56.822
-Thanks, man.
-Sure.

28:56.830 --> 28:58.457
[Xander] They found him
all the way in Alaska.

28:58.460 --> 29:00.246
-In Alaska, man.
-Crazy.

29:00.250 --> 29:03.162
And this Decker guy
told Chris what?

29:03.170 --> 29:05.070
That the psycho nurse
killed a bunch of people

29:05.080 --> 29:06.160
and he needed to find her.

29:06.170 --> 29:07.876
That doesn't make any sense.

29:07.880 --> 29:09.871
'Cause if she really was
this homicidal maniac,

29:09.880 --> 29:12.496
then the cops would have
been looking for Chris,

29:12.500 --> 29:13.910
not this Decker dude,

29:13.920 --> 29:15.911
some whacko fish doctor.

29:15.920 --> 29:18.115
Right. He's lying.

29:18.120 --> 29:19.530
Something happened
in that place.

29:19.540 --> 29:21.417
They wanted to find out
what Chris knew.

29:21.420 --> 29:23.991
Yeah, only he was
too drugged up
to know anything,

29:24.000 --> 29:26.412
so this Decker guy
just let him be.

29:26.420 --> 29:28.035
What'd you find out here?

29:28.040 --> 29:30.918
You ever heard of a company
called Coastal Mills?

29:30.920 --> 29:32.535
No. Why?

29:32.540 --> 29:34.952
They're the ones buying up
all that junk fish

29:34.960 --> 29:36.245
you guys
have been hauling in.

29:36.250 --> 29:38.491
I'm gonna try and figure out
who they are.

29:38.500 --> 29:40.912
Mmm. So maybe
this Decker's connected.

29:40.920 --> 29:42.990
Well, let me know
what you find out.
I gotta go.

29:43.000 --> 29:45.241
Told the guys that
I would buy some pizza
to sop up the whisky.

29:53.460 --> 29:54.700
[Elaine]
Thank you for coming.

29:54.710 --> 29:56.746
Well, thank you
for inviting me.

29:56.750 --> 29:57.910
Thanks.

29:57.920 --> 29:59.615
You have to try
Crab Louis salad.

29:59.620 --> 30:00.666
It's delicious.

30:00.670 --> 30:03.742
Oh. Thanks.

30:03.750 --> 30:05.661
So how's my boy
been lately?

30:05.670 --> 30:06.876
I never hear
from hIm anymore.

30:06.880 --> 30:09.280
Um...

30:09.290 --> 30:11.747
I know the two of you
are busy with your work
at the Center.

30:11.750 --> 30:13.490
Uh, yeah, we have been.

30:13.500 --> 30:15.707
We have this rescue
that's super demanding.

30:15.710 --> 30:17.450
It's eating up
a lot of Ben's time.

30:17.460 --> 30:18.996
He gets deep in it,
you know?

30:19.000 --> 30:20.456
Oh, I know.

30:20.460 --> 30:24.078
So how are you,
the two of you?

30:24.080 --> 30:25.286
Oh, we're fine.

30:25.290 --> 30:27.531
Great, actually.

30:27.540 --> 30:29.030
Good to hear.

30:29.040 --> 30:30.530
What did you rescue?

30:30.540 --> 30:34.112
Uh, a wounded seal pup.

30:38.620 --> 30:40.201
I know what's going on.

30:41.420 --> 30:42.876
Oh.

30:42.880 --> 30:46.919
I love my son,
but he has issues.

30:46.920 --> 30:50.037
Everybody has issues.

30:50.040 --> 30:52.031
Ben's a brilliant thinker,

30:52.040 --> 30:53.701
but he gets lost
in his own mind,

30:53.710 --> 30:55.701
and he--
he shuts people out,

30:55.710 --> 30:56.995
even his own mother.

30:58.540 --> 31:01.998
He does lose himself
in his work.

31:02.000 --> 31:04.616
All his little
wounded creatures.

31:04.620 --> 31:06.576
He's devoted to them.

31:07.960 --> 31:09.996
Are you
his current rescue?

31:10.000 --> 31:12.036
Excuse me?

31:12.040 --> 31:13.496
Oh, don't take that
the wrong way.

31:13.500 --> 31:15.320
I was his first.

31:23.170 --> 31:24.660
[chattering]

31:24.670 --> 31:26.661
[cackling]

31:26.670 --> 31:28.319
What are you watching?

31:28.330 --> 31:30.662
Oh, um...

31:30.670 --> 31:33.457
something stupid
with a monkey.

31:33.460 --> 31:35.166
What can I do you for,
handsome?

31:35.170 --> 31:36.455
Nothing, actually.

31:36.460 --> 31:39.167
I, uh, brought you
a coffee.

31:39.170 --> 31:41.377
Still like it black
with a little bit of sugar?

31:41.380 --> 31:44.326
Since before
you could carry it.

31:44.330 --> 31:47.618
Hey, I was thinking
about taking my dad
out for lunch.

31:47.620 --> 31:48.826
Oh, isn't that sweet,

31:48.830 --> 31:50.161
but he's already at lunch,

31:50.170 --> 31:53.571
with the buyer
from Schoenville Market?

31:53.580 --> 31:55.912
Mind if I wait here
till he gets back?

31:55.920 --> 31:57.706
-Like you have to ask.
-[phone ringing]

31:57.710 --> 31:59.200
Oh.

31:59.210 --> 32:01.075
Pownall Seafood.

32:01.080 --> 32:03.662
Uh, no, no.
He's not here right now.

32:08.120 --> 32:10.577
[Roberta]
No. Uh, no.

32:10.580 --> 32:13.242
-Thank you. Bye.
-[hangs up]

32:19.500 --> 32:20.660
[unsuccessful login beeps]

32:30.460 --> 32:32.325
[unsuccessful login beeps]

32:32.330 --> 32:33.456
[phone ringing]

32:33.460 --> 32:35.576
Oh. What is it?

32:35.580 --> 32:37.536
Pownall Seafood.

32:48.330 --> 32:51.163
[Roberta]
Yes, well, uh, Tuesday.

32:51.170 --> 32:54.617
Tuesday would be wonderful.

33:03.880 --> 33:05.450
Yes, yes.

33:26.620 --> 33:28.611
He was consumed
wrth ﬁnding a cure

33:28.620 --> 33:32.078
or some miracle treatment
to get me back on my feet.

33:32.080 --> 33:33.741
He hated seeing you suffer.

33:33.750 --> 33:35.911
That's sort of what drives him.

33:35.920 --> 33:37.990
Yes. Thank you.

33:38.000 --> 33:40.992
He spent an entire year
online after my accident

33:41.000 --> 33:43.161
researching
spinal cord regeneration

33:43.170 --> 33:46.287
and calling clinics
around the world.

33:46.290 --> 33:47.416
He didn't sleep.

33:47.420 --> 33:49.661
Yeah.

33:49.670 --> 33:52.412
Not sleeping is a thing
with him sometimes.

33:52.420 --> 33:54.456
He fixates.

33:54.460 --> 33:57.452
While he's rescuing you,
you're-- you're everything.

33:59.120 --> 34:01.281
I'm sure he helped you
get over your mother

34:01.290 --> 34:03.702
when you were
first together.

34:03.710 --> 34:06.247
But soon enough,
another wounded creature
comes along,

34:06.250 --> 34:08.571
and he dives
right in after her.

34:10.880 --> 34:12.108
[phone vibrating
and chiming]

34:12.120 --> 34:14.076
Do you need
to get that, dear?

34:18.120 --> 34:20.497
Sorry. I-- I kinda do.

34:20.500 --> 34:22.377
Another drink,
Ms. Pownall?

34:22.380 --> 34:25.247
Um, actually, Andrea,
I'll have the ros
that I love.

34:25.250 --> 34:27.616
Thank you. Maddie?
Would you like something?

34:29.620 --> 34:31.747
Well, if it's Ben, please
tell him I said hello.

34:31.750 --> 34:36.119
Um, I'm so sorry,
but I-- I have to go.

34:36.120 --> 34:37.326
It's, uh...

34:38.960 --> 34:41.167
A new rescue?

34:41.170 --> 34:43.320
It's the same rescue,
actually,

34:43.330 --> 34:45.378
because your son
doesn't give up on things.

34:45.380 --> 34:47.530
And by the way,

34:47.540 --> 34:49.167
I'm not a rescue.

34:49.170 --> 34:51.786
Okay.

34:51.790 --> 34:52.916
Well, thank you
for coming.

34:53.920 --> 34:55.706
Thanks for the salad.

35:01.710 --> 35:06.249
Um, actually, Andrea,
could you make that ros
a martini, please?

35:10.830 --> 35:12.377
So this company,
Coastal Mills,

35:12.380 --> 35:13.824
reached out to my dad,

35:13.830 --> 35:15.070
offered to buy up
all the bycatch

35:15.080 --> 35:16.206
Pownall could deliver.

35:16.210 --> 35:18.371
And-- and who runs
Coastal Mills?

35:18.380 --> 35:20.200
No one knows. _
They don't eXIst online.

35:20.210 --> 35:22.747
No one at Pownall's
ever heard of them.

35:22.750 --> 35:25.878
There's no record
of what happens to the stuff
after they take it.

35:25.880 --> 35:28.201
It's like the trucks
just leave the fisheries

35:28.210 --> 35:30.826
and then disappear.

35:30.830 --> 35:33.879
And Xander said
the Department of Fish and Game

35:33.880 --> 35:35.950
stopped grounding
and fining boats

35:35.960 --> 35:37.780
for overfishing a month ago

35:37.790 --> 35:39.451
right around the same time.

35:39.460 --> 35:42.452
So the government's
letting it happen.

35:44.210 --> 35:46.110
They're making it happen.

35:48.040 --> 35:50.247
[Ben]
They're staving them out

35:50.250 --> 35:52.571
so they can catch
more of them.

36:43.710 --> 36:45.029
There you are.

36:45.040 --> 36:46.371
[hissing]

36:46.380 --> 36:47.699
I've been looking
all over for you.

36:47.710 --> 36:49.610
[hissing]

36:49.620 --> 36:52.953
I thought you might be
by the water.

36:52.960 --> 36:55.110
It's okay.

36:55.120 --> 36:57.611
I'm a friend.

37:01.040 --> 37:03.417
Thought
you might be hungry.

37:13.830 --> 37:15.161
It's okay.

37:15.170 --> 37:16.956
We want the same thing.

37:38.330 --> 37:42.289
Want to go back
to the water?

37:42.290 --> 37:43.780
But not without your sister?

37:47.330 --> 37:48.877
I can help.

37:53.580 --> 37:54.410
You?

37:56.710 --> 37:57.779
Yes.

37:59.330 --> 38:00.456
You can trust me, because...

38:04.420 --> 38:05.956
I am one of you.

38:05.960 --> 38:09.327
[music playing]

38:14.960 --> 38:17.872
They want to hurt us?

38:17.880 --> 38:20.872
They want to catch you.

38:23.750 --> 38:26.287
Danger to go home.

38:27.670 --> 38:28.819
Yes.

38:28.830 --> 38:30.616
[exhales]

38:33.080 --> 38:35.378
Not safe on land.

38:35.380 --> 38:37.530
Not safe in water.

38:39.170 --> 38:41.616
Nowhere is safe.

38:41.620 --> 38:44.418
We're gonna change that.

38:44.420 --> 38:47.787
We'll make it safe
for you

38:47.790 --> 38:49.610
to be wherever
you want to be.

38:51.380 --> 38:53.450
How?

38:55.830 --> 39:00.745
No, screw that, man, okay?

39:00.750 --> 39:04.618
None of this would have
ever happened if that...

39:04.620 --> 39:06.872
that freak fish hadn't
messed me up, you know?

39:06.880 --> 39:09.610
Did you ever ask
this Decker jerk

39:09.620 --> 39:11.827
what they did with the fish?

39:11.830 --> 39:14.458
They're studying it
or something.

39:14.460 --> 39:16.075
Who knows?

39:16.080 --> 39:20.449
Stop asking me
about it, okay?

39:20.460 --> 39:22.451
It's good to be home.

39:22.460 --> 39:24.496
Good to be home.

39:34.710 --> 39:36.371
[line ringing]

39:36.380 --> 39:38.371
Hey, it's Ben.
Leave me a message.

39:38.380 --> 39:39.449
[beeps]

39:39.460 --> 39:42.668
Yo, Ben, dude, um...

39:42.670 --> 39:44.410
I'm just checkin' in,

39:44.420 --> 39:46.536
and wonderin'
what you found out,

39:46.540 --> 39:50.453
'cause, uh...
'cause this Decker guy,

39:50.460 --> 39:54.499
I'm thinkin' he's the one.

39:54.500 --> 39:56.491
That he's behind it all.

39:58.040 --> 40:02.579
[dramatic music playing]

40:02.580 --> 40:05.458
[Xander] Ben, he ain't gonna
stop until he gets her back.

40:23.710 --> 40:26.247
[placid high-pitched calls]

40:30.670 --> 40:35.619
[woman singing Siren song]
